basu (variants: bosu, boshu, bose) is a common indian surname found among bengali hindus. the frequently observed variant is the anglicized form "bose." basus belong to kayastha caste in bengal. the bengali kayasthas evolved as a caste from a category of officials or scribes, between the 5th/6th century ad and 11th/12th century ad, its component elements being mostly brahmins and, according to wink, putative kshatriyas. basus are considered as kulin kayasthas, along with ghoshes and mitras.